1. Allergic reaction: This is a likely diagnosis given the combination of hives, angioedema, and nasal congestion. These are all common symptoms of an allergic reaction. Incontinence and abdominal cramps could also be present depending on the allergen and the severity of the reaction. It is important to identify the allergen and avoid it in the future. Treatment typically involves antihistamines and possibly corticosteroids.

2. Urticaria (hives): This is a common skin condition characterized by itchy, raised welts. It can be caused by allergies, infections, or other factors. Angioedema is a deeper swelling that can affect the face, lips, tongue, or throat. It is often associated with urticaria. Incontinence and abdominal cramps are less common symptoms of urticaria but can occur in some cases.

3. Angioedema: This is a condition that causes swelling of the deep layers of the skin. It can affect the face, lips, tongue, or throat. Angioedema is often associated with urticaria, but it can also occur on its own. Incontinence and abdominal cramps are not typical symptoms of angioedema.

4. Anaphylaxis: This is a severe allergic reaction that can be life-threatening. It typically involves swelling of the airways, difficulty breathing, and a drop in blood pressure. Incontinence and abdominal cramps may also occur. If you suspect anaphylaxis, it is important to seek immediate medical attention.

5. Gastrointestinal infection: This could explain the abdominal cramps and incontinence. Some gastrointestinal infections can also cause hives or angioedema, especially if they are caused by a food allergy.

6. Urinary tract infection (UTI): This is a common infection that can cause urinary urgency, frequency, and incontinence. It is usually accompanied by pain or burning during urination. UTIs are more common in women than men.

7. Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS): This is a chronic disorder that affects the large intestine. Symptoms include abdominal pain, bloating, diarrhea, and constipation. Incontinence may also occur in some cases. IBS is not fully understood, but it is thought to be related to stress, diet, and gut bacteria.

8. Pelvic floor dysfunction: This is a condition that affects the muscles and nerves that support the pelvic organs. It can cause problems with bladder control, bowel control, and sexual function. Incontinence is a common symptom of pelvic floor dysfunction.

9. Medication side effect: Some medications can cause incontinence, abdominal cramps, hives, or angioedema as a side effect. If you are taking any new medications, be sure to review the side effects with your doctor.

10. Other: There are a number of other less common conditions that could cause this combination of symptoms. If you are concerned about your symptoms, it is important to see a doctor for diagnosis and treatment.
